# Indicators of Compromise

This file summarizes the observable indicators and suspicious behaviors identified during the web server compromise investigation.

| Indicator | Type | Security relevance |
|---|---|---|
| Repeated administrator login attempts | Authentication activity | Possible brute-force attack |
| Successful login using a default password | Credential weakness | Initial unauthorized access |
| Unauthorized source-code modification | File or application change | Website compromise |
| Injected JavaScript | Malicious code | Malware delivery mechanism |
| Unexpected executable download | Suspicious file activity | Potential malware payload |
| DNS request to an unknown domain | Network indicator | Malicious redirection |
| HTTP request to an attacker-controlled server | Network indicator | External malicious communication |
| Administrator password changed unexpectedly | Account activity | Legitimate administrator lockout |
| Degraded performance after file execution | Host behavior | Possible malware infection |

## Investigation Notes

The available scenario did not provide concrete IP addresses, domain names, file hashes, filenames, or packet-capture artifacts. Therefore, this repository documents behavioral indicators rather than inventing specific technical indicators.